{
  "texts": [
    "□Theorem 2 requires that h ∈ L ∞ (R +, L q (I)) for some q > 1, in order to exploit Hölder's inequality.",
    "As previously observed, the limit steady state h ∞ (w) (which is known a priori as soon as the main parameters of the problem are fixed) belongs to L q (I) for some q > 1, hence one expects that the solution h(t, w) to equation (44) shares the same regularity of h ∞ (w), as long as one assumes it for the initial datum.",
    "Unfortunately, this is not obvious to demonstrate.",
    "The following lemma ensures however that a weaker version of this fact is true, in the particular case of consensus formation, where h ∞ ∈ L ∞ (I).",
    "As we will show, this property will be enough to prove the convergence of h(w, t) toward h ∞ (w), provided that we impose some additional reasonable constraints on the parameters of the problem."
  ]
}